Hi - I just wanted to clarify the function params for 'policy_improvement' in Assign 1, Question 4, Part B:

def policy_improvement(policy, R, T, V_policy, gamma):

In the lecture slides, policy improvement seemed to require computing the Q(s,a) value for each state-action pair, and so we don't necessarily need to know what specific policy we are using (just the V-pi-i value associated s' in with that policy when computing the Q(s,a) value. As such, my code doesn't make use of the 'policy' parameter at all - is there something I am missing here, or is it reasonable if our code doesn't rely on that parameter for this section?

Is Latex available for the slides?

If not, what are the latex commands I would need to get this nice hanging indentation? (Lec 2) I couldn't figure out how with \begin{align} or \begin{flalign} 

Also, how do you do in-line math symbols in Ed on the same line as normal text?

The rendering code to compare pairwise trajectories seems to always label the left side as preferred over the right side, is that intended? It doesn't seem that the videos obs_1 and obs_2 are correspondingly rearranged to match. Are we supposed to assume the annotator always labels the left side as preferred, or use the actual annotations of 0, 0.5, and 1?

if label == 0.5:
    labels = ["Equally Preferred", "Equally Preferred"]
else:
    labels = ["Preferred", "Not Preferred"]

answers.document:
Hi Dhruba, wow good catch! No, that was not intended; we should not be always labelling the left one as preferred if label != 0.5. I have updated the starter code accordingly in the starter code .zip file in the original HW 3 release post (#468) like so (the label to ordering mapping is based on how we generated the data):

if label == 0.5:
        labels = ["Equally Preferred", "Equally Preferred"]
elif label == 1:
    labels = ["Not Preferred", "Preferred"]
else:
    labels = ["Preferred", "Not Preferred"]


Note: Since this is an error on our end, if you already submitted/wrote an answer using the old code, we will accept those answers as well as long as you explain your reasoning. However, the labels may make more sense if you use the newest code.

